Reviews.main_review:
+ the focus of solving linear assignment problems is relative novel
+ it is a  fully-symmetric solver, which is the desired property

- Overall, this is a feed-forward network that they to solve very general NP-Hard problems. I guess this is too good to be true and likely impractical. I would love to see more realistic work that combines traditional search guided by neural networks;
- The details of sec 3.2 is hard to follow;
- The experiments are preliminary and mostly just ablation studies. Although the authors perform a lot of experiments, most, if not all, baselines results are provided by the authors themselves rather than from the previous paper, which renders the whole section not that informative. This is especially for the 3D point cloud matching problem. There are a lot of networks designed for this task.
- I guess the biggest problem for networks like WeaveNet is its generalizability. I guess for many categories of linear assignment problems where similarity is not important unlike 3D point cloud matching, such networks would not work at all. For example, I am interested to see if the author could test their solver to solve a general SAT problem or a max-SAT problem in which benchmarks are widely available. A section that discusses the limitation should be included IMO.
